# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bill-mckechnie
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The **1907 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1907.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 6, with the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the fourth modern World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 5 on October 12.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Cubs defeated the Tigers, four games to none (with one tie), capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Chicago White Sox from the 1906 season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Beaneaters renamed as the Boston Doves.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The 1907 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 11 with all but the Brooklyn Superbas and Boston Doves playing.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 6.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 12.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] 30 tie games (18 in AL, 12 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 12 with the Chicago Cubs defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1907 World Series in five games (one of which being a tie).
[src:bill-mckechnie/1907-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1909 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the 28th season for the Pittsburgh Pirates franchise, during which they won the National League pennant with a record of 110–42 and their first World Series over the Detroit Tigers.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Led by shortstop Honus Wagner and outfielder-manager Fred Clarke, the Pirates scored the most runs in the majors.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Wagner led the league in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage, and runs batted in.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Pirates owner Barney Dreyfuss opened the Pirates' new ballpark, named Forbes Field, on June 30, 1909.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates' 110 wins remain a team record, a record they set in the last game of the season by beating the Cincinnati Reds 7–4 in muddy conditions on October 5.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] It is in fact the best regular season win percentage by any World Series winning team.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] In the World Series, Pittsburgh faced the American League champion Detroit Tigers, led by triple crown winner Ty Cobb.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The matchup was largely billed as one between the major leagues' two superstars.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1909-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Wagner thoroughly outplayed Cobb, and rookie Babe Adams won all three of his starts, as the Pirates won in seven games.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The **1910 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1910.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the Chicago Cubs and Philadelphia Athletics as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the seventh modern World Series on October 17 and ended with Game 5 on October 23.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The Athletics defeated the Cubs, four games to one, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Pittsburgh Pirates from the 1909 season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The 1910 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] For the first time, Opening Day, which took place on April 14, featured all sixteen teams.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the regular season on October 9, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season was on October 15.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 17 and October 23.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] 26 tie games (19 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 17 and ended on October 23 with the Philadelphia Athletics defeating the Chicago Cubs in the 1910 World Series in five games.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators would play their last games at the original National Park with a doubleheader on October 6 against the Boston Red Sox.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The park burned down in March 1911 and the Senators moved into a new National Park for the start of the 1911 season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox would play their last game at South Side Park on June 27, having played ten seasons there going back to their inaugural 1901 season, and opened White Sox Park on July 1, where they would go on to play for 81 seasons through 1990.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The **1912 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1912.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 6, with the New York Giants and Boston Red Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the ninth modern World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 8 on October 16.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Giants, four games to three (with one tie), capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1903.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1911 season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each league.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] During the season, *Harper's Weekly* conducted a detailed accounting of the expenses of major league clubs, reaching a figure of approximately $175,000 to $200,000.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Rustlers renamed as the Boston Braves.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 11, featured all sixteen teams, only the second time every team has started their season on the same day (first being two years prior with the 1910 season).
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 16.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] 13 tie games (8 in AL, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 16 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the New York Giants in the 1912 World Series in seven games.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 season saw two teams play their last seasons at their respective venues.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 season saw three teams play in new venues.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, was renamed to Robison Field by Helene Britton, named after her father and uncle, Frank and Stanley Robison, respectively.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1912-major-league-baseball-season] To accommodate for large crowds, the New York Highlanders would play three home games at the Brush Stadium, home of the New York Giants, on May 30 and a doubleheader on September 2.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The **1913 major league baseball season** began on April 9, 1913.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 5, with the New York Giants and Philadelphia Athletics as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the tenth World Series on October 7 and ended with Game 5 on October 11.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] In the third iteration of this World Series matchup, the Athletics defeated the Giants, four games to one, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1911.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Boston Red Sox from the 1912 season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] This was the third of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each league.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Trolley Dodgers shortened its name to the Brooklyn Dodgers and the New York Highlanders renamed as the New York Yankees.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The 1913 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 9 with a game between the Philadelphia Phillies and Brooklyn Dodgers, while American League Opening Day took place the following day, with all AL teams but the Chicago White Sox and Cleveland Naps, playing.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 5.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 7 and October 11.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The National League ruled that umpires could no longer scout for teams, as was the case when Umpire Cy Rigler was being paid $2,200 (equivalent to $71,700 in 2025) by the Philadelphia Phillies for his role in having the team sign a pitcher, Eppa Rixey.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] 21 tie games (5 in AL, 16 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 7 and ended on October 11 with the Philadelphia Athletics defeating the New York Giants in the 1913 World Series in five games.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The 1913 season saw two teams move to two venues.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox renamed White Sox Park to Comiskey Park, named after team owner Charles Comiskey.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Braves play two doubleheaders on April 19 and May 30 at the home of the Boston Red Sox at Fenway Park to accommodate large crowds.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The **1914 Indianapolis Hoosiers season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The Hoosiers won the inaugural Federal League championship, finishing 88–65, 1½ games ahead of the Chicago Federals.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] The offensive star of the team was outfielder Benny Kauff, who led the league in batting average (.370), runs scored (120), and stolen bases (75).
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Future Hall of Famers Edd Roush and Bill McKechnie also saw significant playing time, and Indianapolis scored a league-high 762 runs.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-indianapolis-hoosiers-season] Their rotation ace, Cy Falkenberg, went 25–16 with a 2.22 earned run average; he topped the circuit with 236 strikeouts.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The **1914 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1914, with the first game of the inaugural major league season of the Federal League (having previously existed as a minor league the year before).
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The league declared itself as a "third major league", with its own eight teams, in competition with the established National and American Leagues.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League regular season ended on October 6 with the Boston Braves as champions, and the American League regular season concluded the next day with the Philadelphia Athletics as champions.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League season ended on October 10, and saw the Indianapolis Hoosiers winning the Federal League pennant.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the National and American Leagues began with Game 1 of the 11th World Series on October 9 and ended with Game 4 on October 13.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Braves swept the Athletics in four games, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Both the National and American Leagues rejected offers by the Federal League for a postseason matchup.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1913 season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each of the established National and American Leagues.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers renamed as the Brooklyn Robins.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The major-league status of the Federal League was confirmed by the Special Baseball Records Committee (as convened by then-Commissioner of Baseball William Eckert) in 1969.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The 1914 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League, National League, and Federal League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format first put in place for the 1904 season, and which lasted until the 140-game schedule of 1919.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Most teams played more than 154 games, due to tie games (called on account of darkness or weather) that had to be replayed; tie games are excluded from team standings, but the statistics of individual players are included in their season totals.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had its Opening Day on April 13, with a game between Buffalo and Baltimore.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day for the American and National Leagues was on April 14, and featured all 16 teams of those leagues, only the third time those two leagues started their season on the same day (the 1912 season had been the second).
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League had its final day of the regular season on October 6, while the American League's final day of the regular season was October 7.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series between AL and NL champions took place between October 9 and October 13.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had the final day of its regular season on October 10.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] 43 tie games (18 in AL, 10 in NL, 15 in FL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 9 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Braves sweeping the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1914 World Series in four games.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National and American Leagues refused a postseason against the Federal League.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Across two leagues, Dave Davenport tied as a leader in saves at 6 (2 with the Cincinnati Reds of the NL and 4 with the St.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Note: Attendance data for Federal League teams is unavailable.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] They previously played their on August 1 and August 8.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] In all, 29 of their 79 home games were played at Fenway Park.
[src:bill-mckechnie/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The team would only play at Fenway through July of the following season.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie was born on August 7, 1886, to Archibald and Mary McKechnie, two Scottish immigrants who had settled in Wilkinsburg, Pennsylvania, shortly before Bill was born.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie made his major league debut in 1907 with the Pittsburgh Pirates, appearing in three games, before reemerging with the team in 1910 in a more substantial role.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] His best offensive season came in 1914 with the Hoosiers, when he scored 107 runs, batted .304 and stole 47 bases.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] In 846 games over 11 major league seasons, McKechnie posted a .251 batting average (713-for-2843) with 319 runs, 8 home runs, 240 RBI, 127 stolen bases and 190 bases on balls.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Defensively, he recorded an overall .954 fielding percentage playing at third, second, first base and shortstop.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] In 1913, McKechnie had his worst season as a full-time player, batting only .134.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] However, Yankees manager Frank Chance thought McKechnie had a keen baseball mind, and had him sit next to him on the bench during games.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Two years later, McKechnie got his first taste of managerial duties, when he served as player-manager of the Newark Peppers of the Federal League, leading the team to a 54–45 record.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] After he retired as a player, he managed for a year in the minors before assuming the helm of the Pirates in 1922.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] He managed the Pirates from 1922 to 1926, St.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Louis Cardinals again after they rehired him in 1929, Boston Braves from 1930 to 1937, and Cincinnati Reds from 1938 to 1946.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] He compiled 1,896 wins and 1,723 losses for a .524 winning percentage over his managerial career.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] His teams won four National League pennants (1925, 1928, 1939 and 1940) and two World Series championships (1925 and 1940), and he remains the only manager to win National League pennants with three teams (Pittsburgh, St.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] He took over the Pirates in the middle of the 1922 season, as George Gibson was fired after going 32–33.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie led the Pirates to 53 wins in 90 games to maneuver them into a third-place finish in the National League.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Third place awaited the Pirates for the next two years, but the 1925 season proved a breakthrough as the Pirates went 95–58 and won the pennant, which was the first pennant for the club in sixteen years, led by future Hall of Famers such as Max Carey, Kiki Cuyler, and Pie Traynor.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Pittsburgh faced off against the Washington Senators, who had won the World Series the previous year while brought on fellow Hall of Famers in manager Bucky Harris, Stan Coveleski, Goose Goslin, Sam Rice, and Walter Johnson.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] The Pirates won just one of the first four games, needing to win to drive the Series back to Pittsburgh.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] They held the Senators (who had scored fourteen runs in the past four games to seven for Pittsburgh) to five total runs in the next two games to force a Game 7 with Johnson on the mound against Ray Kremer.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Amid rain and fog in Forbes Field, the Senators built an early lead with four runs in the first inning.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] However, the Pirates responded each time Washington would score, and this included a 7–6 game going into the bottom of the eighth inning.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Two outs were followed by three hits, a fielder's choice, and a walk; Cuyler hit a two-run double off Johnson for the go-ahead runs as Red Oldham got the save to clinch Pittsburgh's title.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] It would be the last World Series title for the Pirates for 35 years.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie's tenure in Pittsburgh unraveled the following year when several of his players thought part-owner, vice president and de facto bench coach Fred Clarke was undermining him.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Several of them thought Clarke was trying to regain the job he had held from 1900 to 1915.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Three veteran players—Max Carey, Carson Bigbee and Babe Adams—demanded Clarke's removal from the bench.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie, who by inclination was a player's manager, initially appeared to support them.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] However, fearing that he'd be seen as opposing the ownership, he was forced to denounce his own players.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Ownership struck fast and hard, releasing Bigbee and Adams and waiving Carey.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] The dispute cut the legs out from under the Pirates, who fell to third with a 84–69 (with four ties) record.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] He was replaced by Donie Bush, who had short-term success with the Pirates, including winning the pennant in his first season with the club, although his squabbles with Cuyler lead to a subsequent trade and Bush's resignation two years later.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie was brought in as a coach for the 1927 season for the St.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] After the year ended, he replaced player-manager Bob O'Farrell, who was given a $5,000 raise to step down for McKechnie.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] The Cardinals finished the 1928 season in first place with a record 95 wins and 59 losses.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] They were swept in the World Series by the New York Yankees.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie left the club after the World Series.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Billy Southworth started the 1929 season with 43 wins and 45 losses.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Gabby Street managed for a game before McKechnie returned as manager.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] He finished the 1929 season with a record of 34 wins and 29 losses.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie was hired to manage the Boston Braves in 1930, replacing Emil Fuchs, who had added manager to his title of owner when he had to trade Rogers Hornsby to try to stay solvent.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Financial troubles would plague the Braves alongside other teams in the Great Depression era.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] His first Braves team finished 70–84 for a sixth-place finish in the NL, which was actually an improvement from their record of 56–98 the previous year.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie was not nearly as successful in Boston as he was at his other managerial stops, but he managed to finish "fourth or fifth with teams that should have been eighth," according to baseball historian Lee Allen.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] In eight years, he had a winning record four times while finishing in the first division (top four) twice.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] In 1933, they finished 83–71 to have their first winning season in twelve years, doing so while finishing fourth, nine games behind New York.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] They finished 78–73 the next year and finished 16 games behind St.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] The bottom fell out in 1935, a season in which Babe Ruth returned to play in the city of Boston for the first time in 16 years, with Fuchs also giving him duties of vice president and assistant manager, although these were more ceremonial than anything.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] According to Allen, McKechnie claimed that Ruth's presence made it nearly impossible to enforce discipline.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Ruth drew a huge salary, and lived apart from the team on the road.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Additionally, years of high living had rendered him a shadow of his former self.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] He could no longer run, and committed so many errors that three pitchers threatened to go on strike if he was in the lineup.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Ruth stopped hitting as well, and retired only a month into the season after hitting .181.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Despite fielding essentially the same team that finished fourth a year earlier, the Braves crumbled to a record of 38–115, the worst record in modern National League history and the second worst in modern major league history.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] The team improved in the next two years, going 71–83 (with three ties) and 79–73 before McKechnie was hired to manage the Cincinnati Reds in 1938.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] According to one baseball reference work, McKechnie had a poor sense of direction, which did not improve when, as the Reds' manager, he began traveling by plane.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] He arrived in an airport when the Reds were to play the Pirates at Forbes Field.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] He hailed a taxi and asked the driver to take him to the Schenley Hotel.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie gave him the names of the nearby streets.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] "Never heard of them either", the cabbie said.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] "How long have you been driving a cab here? the manager asked.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] "Twenty-five years and then some", said the driver, "But so help me I never heard of the Schenley Hotel!
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Where do you think you are?" "Pittsburgh", McKechnie said.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] "Pittsburgh, hell!" retorted the driver.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie was an unusual kind of manager for his era.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] A very religious man, he did not smoke, drink alcohol or use profanity.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] When he had a problem player who was likely to go out carousing, McKechnie's simple solution was to room with him.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] In his first season with the Reds, he led them to an 82–68–1 record, finishing 4th in the NL behind the Chicago Cubs.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] In his second year, he led them to a 97–57–2 record, finishing 1st by 4+1⁄2 games over the St.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] This was McKechnie's third pennant, with each occurring with a different team.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] In the World Series that year, they were swept by the New York Yankees.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] In the following year, the Reds managed to improve, winning 100 games (a team first) while winning the NL once again, this time by 12 games over the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] In the World Series that year, they beat the Detroit Tigers in seven games.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] The Reds didn't win more than 90 games in the rest of McKechnie's tenure, but they did manage to finish with a winning record in four of his six final years, including a 2nd place in 1943.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] 1946 was his final year with the team, managing them to a 64–86 record (with 2 ties), with Hank Gowdy managing the final four games.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] His last game managed was on September 25 at St.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] He was hired as a coach to be the right-hand man of young Cleveland Indians manager Lou Boudreau the following year.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Once, when Larry Doby (the first African American player in the American League was playing for the Indians, McKechnie prevented him from going up a barrier to confront a racist heckler, saying that it would "ruin you, not him".
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] The Boudreau–McKechnie Indians won a World Series in 1948.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie coached with Boudreau for five seasons, with the Indians (1947–49) and Boston Red Sox (1952–53).
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1962 and into the Cincinnati Reds Hall of Fame in 1967.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie died at age 79 in Bradenton, Florida.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] The Pirates' spring training home, McKechnie Field in Bradenton, was named after him until the name changed to LECOM Park in 2017.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] McKechnie's son Bill Jr. was the farm system director of the Cincinnati Redlegs in the mid-1950s and later served as president of the Florida State League (1961–1962) and Pacific Coast League (1969–1973).
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] He was also the father of former Syracuse radio station WNDR sportscaster Jim McKechnie.
[src:bill-mckechnie/bill-mckechnie] Bill McKechnie Jr.'s son Bill III was born April 20, 1940, and died of cancer in Florida on June 17, 2006.
